ce:section.ce:para:
Citric acid and urea were utilized as carbon source and nitrogen source respectively to prepare CQDs through a solvothermal method in ethylene glycol, in which urea provided sufficient surface amino groups. The synthesized CQDs showed good solubility in water. Subsequently, a “proton relay” was introduced onto CQDs through the amidation reaction to accelerate proton transfer in PCET. EDC and NHS were used to mediate the formation of amide bonds between amino groups of CQDs and the carboxyl groups of EDTA molecules (
                           Fig. S1
                        ).

XPS and FT-IR (Fig. 2
                        ) were employed to demonstrate the successful connection between EDTA and CQDs. In the FT-IR spectra of CQDs and EDTA-CQDs, the absorption bands at 3410 cm−1 and 3200 cm−1 correspond to the vibrations of O-H and N-H bonds respectively, while the vibrations in the range of 2860 cm−1 to 2960 cm−1 are attributed to C-H bonds [4,42,63]. In comparison to CQDs, the N-H stretching vibration band of –NH2 group is weakened due to its involvement in the amidation reaction, and the CO stretching vibration peak of EDTA-CQDs slightly redshifts to 1590 cm−1, indicating the coupling between CQDs and EDTA, resulting in a stronger absorption peak related to the surface EDTA molecules. The significant signal around 1400 cm−1 also demonstrates the formation of C-N group through the amidation reaction [64]. In the C1s XPS spectrum of EDTA-CQDs, the peaks of oxygen-containing groups with higher binding energies, such as C-OH and C-CO, show a reduced intensity (8.08 % → 6.2 %, 15.5 % → 8%), while the intensity of COOH increases (4.5 %→5.3 %), indicating the introduction of EDTA with high carboxyl content leads to a decrease in the total oxygen element ratio (3.53 %) but an increase in carboxyl group content (0.8 %) (
                           Table S1
                        ). Additionally, a new N1s peak appears at 402 eV in the EDTA-CQDs system, representing the formation of amide bond [42] (Fig. 2
                        d). The positions of graphitic nitrogen, pyridinic nitrogen, and pyrrolic nitrogen shift towards lower energy levels compared to CQDs. This may be due to the electron delocalization effect of the amide coupling in the EDTA-CQDs molecules, also indicating the successful functionalization of CQDs through the amidation reaction.

The carboxyl group of EDTA and the amino group of CQDs are key factors in the amidation reaction, leading to the formation of amide bond connection. Considering the influence of group numbers and chain length of APCAs on photocatalytic performance, different APCAs substances (
                           Table S2
                        ) were first used to functionalize CQDs, including NTA (One tertiary amino groups and three carboxyl groups), EDTA (Two tertiary amino groups and four carboxyl groups), and EDDS (Two secondary amino groups and four carboxyl groups). All APCA-CQDs display characteristic amide bond N1s peaks (
                           Fig. S4
                        ). The photocatalytic performance of APCA-CQDs is significantly higher compared with AQ functionalized CQDs (20.7 mg/L), indicating that the amidation connection has a significant promoting effect on PHP. Under the irradiation of 300 W xenon lamp, the H2O2 production rates of NTA-CQDs, EDTA-CQDs, and EDDS-CQDs synthesized at a mass ratio of 1:1 at 1 h are 32.1 mg/L, 44.5 mg/L, and 37.0 mg/L, respectively (Fig. 5

                        a). Tertiary amines cannot undergo amidation reactions, therefore both NTA and EDTA are connected to the amino groups of CQDs through their carboxyl groups. EDTA can provide more carboxyl groups, produce more amide bonds, and thus has higher H2O2 yield. EDDS and EDTA have the same number of carboxyl groups, but the longer chain of EDDS may hinder the reaction between O2 and CQDs and then impose negative influence on the electron transfer, resulting in lower H2O2 yield. The DO variation curves (
                           Fig. S5
                        ) during the photocatalytic reaction also show that the order of oxygen consumption rate in the three systems is EDTA-CQDs＞EDDS-CQDs＞NTA-CQDs.

To verify the effect of amidation connection between EDTA and CQDs on enhancing the photocatalytic production of H2O2, the photocatalytic performances of EDTA, CQDs, EDTA + CQDs, and EDTA-CQDs were compared. The results show that EDTA itself has no catalytic effect, and direct mixing it with CQDs slightly improves the photocatalytic efficiency. The directly added EDTA captures holes and promotes the separation of photogenerated e−/h+ pairs, thereby increasing the photocatalytic activity. The H2O2 yield (44.5 mg/L, 2200 μmol g−1h−1) of EDTA-CQDs with amide bonds is 4.3 times higher than that of CQDs (10.3 mg/L, 512 μmol g−1h−1) (Fig. 5
                        b), and significantly superior to other reported carbon based photocatalysts to date (
                           Table S3
                        ), indicating that installing a proton relay on the surface of CQDs can significantly promote the PCET reaction and increase the yield of PHP. It is worth noting that there is no significant increase in the H2O2 yield of CQDs presented in this study after adding ethanol as a sacrificial electron donor (
                           Fig. S6
                        ). It can be seen that CQDs photocatalyst has a certain ability to self-supply proton and can effectively produce H2O2 without the use of sacrificial agents.

Long term stability is another key requirement for developing efficient photocatalysts. Therefore, the reusability of EDTA-CQDs was also investigated and the results were shown in Fig. S7. It was found that EDTA-CQDs maintained a high H2O2 yield (100 %, 92 %, 95 %) in three cycles of reaction. This corresponds to the recovery of dissolved oxygen shown in Fig. 4b. The XPS characterization (
                           Fig. S8
                        ) of EDTA-CQDs after multiple repeated experiments showed that the proportion of oxygen-containing functional groups in the catalyst remained relatively stable, and the content of amide bond did not significantly decrease after long-term testing. FT-IR and XRD analysis (
                           Fig. S9
                        ) also showed there was little change in the surface functional groups and crystal forms of catalyst, indicating that the structure EDTA-CQDs was stable during the photocatalytic process. In addition, negligible H2O2 decomposition (＜0.5 %) was observed in EDTA-CQDs system. Most reports on PHP require aeration to increase the concentration of O2 in the solution. It is worth noting that the H2O2 yield obtained under air condition in this study is only 5 % lower than that under O2 aeration conditions. In previous studies, replacing pure O2 with air resulted in a 30 %∼50 % decrease in yield [68,69]. As shown in Table S3, the PHP efficiency of EDTA-CQDs in air has exceeded that of most photocatalysts under O2 aeration. It can be seen that EDTA-CQDs can fully utilize O2, and achieve efficient photocatalytic production of H2O2 at the environmental O2 level, which is of great significance for their direct application in practical environment. Overall, these results indicate that EDTA-CQDs are ideal candidates for PHP, exhibiting excellent H2O2 generation performance and photochemical stability in the absence of sacrificial agents.

According to the VB and CB positions of EDTA-CQDs, the production of H2O2 mainly depends on the PCET reaction of electrons generated in the CB. The VB positions of both CQDs and EDTA-CQDs cannot meet the demand for H2O2 production. Using NaIO3 as an electronic scavenger, it was found that neither EDTA-CQDs nor CQDs systems generate H2O2 (Fig. 7

                        a), indicating that H2O2 comes from the reduction of O2 rather than the oxidation of H2O. In addition, in the absence of O2 source, almost no H2O2 is produced in both systems (Table 1
                        ), indicating that H2O2 is mainly generated by consuming O2 continuously absorbed from air into water, with almost no oxygen generated from hole oxidation of water.

To elucidate the mechanism of introducing EDTA to promote PCET, the XPS N1s and O1s spectra of CQDs and EDTA-CQDs before and after the photocatalytic reaction were compared. It was found that the N1s spectrum of CQDs showed little change before and after the reaction, while the main change in the O1s spectrum was a decrease of 1.95 % in hydroxyl groups (C-OH) and an increase of 1.6 % in carbonyl groups (C–CO) (Fig. 8
                        ). It can be seen that some C-OH is consumed to generate CO, indicating the C-OH groups on the surface of CQDs provide protons for the ORR reaction. The addition of ethanol did not significantly change the yield of H2O2, indicating that CQDs have the ability to self-supply protons, and the photocatalytic reaction prioritizes the use of protons provided by themselves. In the N1s spectrum of EDTA-CQDs, the peak of amide bond was reduced by 10.2 % after photoreaction (26.4 % → 16.2 %), indicating that it may also act as the proton donor for the ORR. In addition, the C-OH content in the O1s spectrum decreases by 4.54 %, showing a greater consumption under the same reaction conditions (Fig. 8
                        a, b). This likely indicates that the proton activity of EDTA-CQDs is higher [75,76]. That is, in addition to introducing new proton donor, the amide bond also plays an important role in activating protons, i.e. the formation of amide bonds on CQDs enhances the utilization of C–OH.

To further validate the above viewpoint, the C1s, N1s, and O1s spectra of EDTA-CQDs synthesized in different mass ratios (1:1, 1:2, 1:3) were compared (Fig. 9
                        ). XPS analyses of catalysts with different ratios of EDTA and CQDs show that there is a linear relationship between the surface functional group content of catalyst and the production rate of H2O2, which is positively correlated with the content of amide bond (R2 = 0.998) (Fig. 9
                        d). Further demonstrating the important role of amide bonds as proton relay.

In this study, pyridine probe infrared analysis was also utilized to demonstrate the changes in the local proton concentration. Pyridine can act as a basic molecule probe to interact with the Brønsted acid sites on the catalyst surface. According to the literature, the peak at 1530 cm−1 is attributed to the adsorption of pyridine on the Brønsted acid sites [64]. Compared to CQDs, the intensity of this peak in EDTA-CQDs is significantly enhanced (
                           Fig. S10
                        ), reflecting CQDs connected to EDTA via amide bonds have more Brønsted acid sites that can release protons.
